# Tableau — Brain Dump 

Basics & workflow
- Duplicate sheets.
- Duplicate dashboards.
- Duplicate fields to keep color the same across sheets.
- Copy from one dashboard to another; pasted items often become floating.
- Save frequently — Tableau sometimes recovers unsaved versions after a crash.
- Create a dummy Excel workbook to test behaviors and to share with others.
- Use extracts (.hyper) for large data / performance or offline; use live connections for real-time needs.
- Edit connection to point to the correct workbook/version (Data → Edit Connection).
- Refresh data source and Extracts. Schedule extract refreshes as needed.
- Use Tableau Prep for cleaning data.
- Use Data Interpreter to clean Excel imports.
- Manage metadata to change workbook field names.
- Replace data source: Data → Replace Data Source.
- To see which sheets use which data source, inspect Data pane or use Replace Data Source to detect dependencies.
- When testing, use small datasets to reproduce issues.

Sheets & views
- View data: Right-click → View Data → Full Data to see rows without opening Excel.
- View underlying data by right click on the viz → View Data → Full Data → Show fields (all).
- Copy crosstab to Excel: Worksheet → Copy → Crosstab.
- Copy sheet format / copy formatting of sheets in Tableau.
- Right click a sheet to add a worksheet or copy.
- Right click sheet tab → Copy Formatting (use carefully).
- To unhide headers: Rows & Columns → Show Headers, or use Layout pane.
- Add captions: Worksheet → Show Caption.
- Show filter by clicking on sheets — show filters in worksheet.
- Edit in Shelf to avoid creating new fields repeatedly.
- To create instructions in the dashboard, create an overlay image or use an image overlay (Figma or exported overlay).
- To exit presentation mode: click the icon below.
- Double click to select the second container, triple click to select a container that contains both.
- Bring floating orders to front. Use Bring to Front / Send to Back appropriately.
- If a view doesn’t show, check containers and whether the sheet is hidden or used elsewhere.
- If view resizes strangely after show/hide, ensure containers are consistently placed and use nested containers.
- User Specific Views, to show data to certain audience (similar to row-level security)
- Add to Context and using attr()

Dashboards & common dashboards
- Build dashboards using tiled or floating objects.
- Use device layouts or fixed size for consistent display.
- To resize worksheets automatically: click on the sheet arrow and uncheck "Fixed height".
- Use blank objects (create a blank and set height to 10 and set background color) as separators.
- Create blank separators with black/gray backgrounds to visually separate sections.
- Use layout pane in dashboard view to view and change object sizes and padding.
- Create dashboards I made: Decisions Dashboard (decisions type by lines, implementation period), Production Dashboard (quantity by period names with filters), Missed Demand Dashboard (missed quantities by period names by product), Capacity Dashboard (average ratio by lines by periods with filters), Staffing Dashboard (staffing metrics), Investment Dashboard (investment summary by lines/plants/period).
- Copy dashboard to PowerPoint: prefer Export → Image or copy image, not screen capture. (If you replace original picture with same name, the workbook may update).
- Copy dashboard image to PowerPoint (don’t do screen capture if possible).
- Dashboard instructions in PowerPoint: include instructions as overlay image.
- Navigation object: navigate to dashboards or worksheets.
- Responsive designs for specific device layouts — design separate device layouts.
- Publish workbook: Server → Publish Workbook (choose project, name, tags). For Tableau Cloud sign in to https://online.tableau.com.
- Publish data source separately when appropriate.
- Print views from desktop: File → Page Setup, then File → Print.

Containers, layout & formatting
- Container types: Horizontal vs Vertical; Tiled vs Floating.
- Nested containers are useful to hide/show filters and have the dashboard resize without distributing everything evenly.
- Use "Distribute contents evenly" if you don’t see what you put in the container.
- When you see the dashed outline, you know the item will be placed in the container on release.
- Fix height/width when consistent size required; unclick fixed height to auto-resize.
- Outer padding, inner padding and background shading create spacing and faux borders.
- To create borders around sheets, set outer container background shading or use Layout → Add border/padding.
- To change the outer padding: edit layout or use the Layout pane.
- To create shadow effect: bottom and right outer pane set to 5, background gray, include a border line with color.
- If you can’t align text in dashboard view, go to the sheet and align text there (Format → Alignment → Text).
- If the container doesn't have the pin icon, check container type or nested state and item hierarchy.
- Remove a container individually: right-click container → Remove.
- Edit item hierarchy to see nested containers and background shading.
- Place containers consistently to ensure perfect alignment when showing/hiding labels.
- Use placeholders (text) and click Distribute contents evenly to show hidden sheets when using show/hide.
- When dashline appears while dragging, the item will go into that container upon release.
- For tiled containers that must have a specific size, use fixed width/height and distribute contents evenly.
- To fit a tiled dashboard into a vertical object, experiment with nested containers and fixed sizes.

Formatting details & quirks
- Pane number formatting (instead of axis number formatting) — useful for crosstabs.
- Rotate label by clicking an axis label and selecting Rotate Label (rotation doesn’t change font size).
- Edit format of reference line to change color for better contrast.
- Format filters in sheets not dashboard; formatting filters in dashboard sometimes disappears.
- To format the entire table: click the capital "A" to apply global formatting.
- To format a filter: right-click format filter and set controls in the drop down — don’t edit title (isn’t permanent).
- Special values (e.g., hide 0): Right-click measure pill → Format → Pane → Special Values → Hide.
- Changing directions when formatting numbers: set custom formatting.
- To change order of stacked bar chart: drag entries in the legend and change order there.
- Field labels at bottom to avoid overcrowding.
- Use the Layout pane to check sheet height when things look uneven; compare heights and edit fixed height to make items equal.
- To push text alignments to bottom to fix the unevenness between a vertical with fixed height and a vertical with no fixed height, use Layout pane.
- If formatting keeps disappearing, check whether formatting applied at sheet vs dashboard level, floating vs tiled, or if the workbook or data source version changed.

Filters, lists & filter behavior
- Filter: apply to selected sheets only when needed.
- Use "Apply to selected sheets" on a filter.
- Use "Only relevant values" to limit list based on selections.
- Using all values in the data source in the drop down arrow & show relevant only option.
- Custom value in filter -> single value.
- Filter on dimensions in columns or row shelves.
- Show all button (base plan vs optimizer) — show all or reset filters.
- Use contextual filters to change order and performance.
- Include "show filter label for row or columns" — Analysis → Table layout → Show filter label.
- If a filter displays all values but you want certain scenarios, use "Only relevant values".
- To unselect all applied sheets: choose "only this worksheet".
- If copying filters across workbooks, watch for alias differences (asterisk indicates alias).
- Add cash flow filter to filter out 0 values & remove rows & columns with missing or 0 values.
- To show empty columns / show missing periods: make sure to include all period members in the domain or enable “show missing values”.
- To see excluded values: go to the filter and retrieve it there.

Parameters, sets & grouping
- Use parameter along with calculated field.
- Parameter to show/hide containers: current value only is available when dragging into filter; do each sheet separately.
- Parameter-driven sheet selector — use parameter to swap sheets or control visibility.
- Parameter limitations: when you drag a parameter into the filter shelf, only the parameter's current value is available.
- Use parameters to control visibility (control zone visibility).
- Sets: use sets for IN/OUT logic, top N, and comparisons.
- Grouping columns: grouping to merge members.
- Difference between group and set: group merges members; set is IN/OUT.
- Create folders in Data pane (works in some modes); create a read-later folder for Tableau resources.

Actions & interactivity
- Make a button with actions.
- Show/Hide button: make show/hide button and place in container; nested containers help resizing.
- Add actions within dashboard: filter actions, highlight actions, URL actions, navigation actions.
- Actions will automatically add filters to the filter shelf if relevant.
- Visual tooltips — referencing another sheet; insert sheets into tooltips.
- Highlighter only works for discrete fields.
- Use navigation object: navigate to other dashboards or sheets.
- Create instructions overlay via an image (overlay) or Figma overlay.
- Add action within dashboard for swap or filter; actions can be used for sheet swap.
- Actions can also be used to create interactive buttons to navigate between dashboards and worksheets.
- Use "Highlight" actions for focusing discrete categories.
- Visual tooltip: sometimes hide other tooltips when using a visual tooltip.

Marks, charts & visual techniques
- Pane vs axis formatting and when to use each.
- Charts: bar, stacked bar, dual axis, combined axis charts, Gantt, treemap, bullet chart, highlight table, pyramid chart, histogram.
- Row banding (shading) — may not work for highlight tables (mark-based coloring).
- Analysis → Stack Marks off to create overlapping bar chart; adjust mark size with Show Me.
- Stacked bar chart: to change order drag the legend to change stacking order.
- Dual axis chart tips: axes are independent; format axes separately; sync axes when needed.
- Combined axis charts — trick: overlay measures on the same axis.
- Overlap bars by turning stacking off and adjusting size.
- Manual sort by clicking dimension header (plant name or line name) in the column.
- Sorting stacked bars: drag the legend entries to reorder.
- For Gantt charts: create calculated fields for Gantt and sorting using calculated fields (LOD expressions often used).
- Create a highlight table: calculated field named One = 1 and drag it onto Size, then increase size to fit cell.
- For highlight table formatting, adjust Marks → Label → spacing.
- Pyramid chart: create two charts and hide one (reverse) or use other pyramid techniques.
- Bullet chart: use bar + reference lines.
- Trend line: works with two numeric fields (or numeric measure and numeric dimension).
- Reference band and reference distribution: use for summary shading and distributions.
- Reference line on another value — create a relationship and add that field to Details, then add a reference line.
- Mark annotation: annotate specific marks with notes.
- Mark-level details: drag multiple fields into Details to add granularity.
- Use ATTR when expecting a single but it may vary.

Colors & shapes
- Create custom palettes using Preferences.tps in My Tableau Repository (open with Notepad).
- Add custom shapes: put shapes in My Tableau Repository → Shapes and reload shapes.
- Copy color code by right-clicking color pill.
- Use color-blind-friendly palettes. Tools: https://colorkit.io/ and https://coolors.co/
- Color-blindness simulator: https://pilestone.com/pages/color-blindness-simulator-1
- If Tableau smart color not working, change dashboard size or mark size.
- Set the number to contrast the background (smart color).
- To paste many colors: hold Shift, click first color, scroll, then click last color to select a range.
- For diverging traffic-light style use red-green-gold diverging or custom palette.

Tooltips & visual tooltips
- Visual tooltips: insert sheets into tooltips to show another viz.
- Use visual tooltips for bar charts to reveal more info; usually show one field for clarity.
- Usually hide other tooltips when you have visual tooltips active.

Table layout & crosstabs
- Table layout: show filter by clicking on sheets; Analysis → Table Layout → Show Filter Label; show filter label for row or columns.
- To view height of a sheet click Layout in the dashboard view.
- Use Table layout options for column/row banding and show filter labels.
- Copy crosstab to Excel.
- To format entire table, use the capital "A".
- To change default aggregation: go to Default Properties → Aggregation or Default Properties → Number Format.
- Add totals: various ways — use Analysis → Totals.

Calculations, LOD & table calcs
- Calculated fields reverse engineering: duplicate sheets, isolate measures to debug.
- LOD calculations: FIXED, INCLUDE, EXCLUDE — e.g., {FIXED [Dim]: SUM([Measure])}.
- Create calculated fields for Gantt chart and sorting (sometimes LOD expressions).
- ELSEIF (not ELSE IF) syntax nuance.
- Table calculations: Quick Table Calculation → Compute Using (Table Across vs Table Down) and specific dimensions.
- ATTR function returns attribute; useful for single-valued fields in multi-row contexts.
- Use IF, IIF, CASE, nested logic; logical functions are black in editor; other functions are blue.
- Use ZN and IFNULL to replace null values with zero.
- Create dynamic titles that change based on filter selections (example video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4NWCQzyz7C8).
- Custom formatting of average line or reference line text: edit reference line formatting and use custom text.
- Reverse engineering: duplicate sheets & test calculations in separate sheets to validate measures.
- Create custom date calculations: DATEPARSE, DATETRUNC, DATEADD, DATEDIFF, DATENAME, DATEPART.
- DATETRUNC returns a truncated date (e.g., month start), DATEPART returns discrete parts (month number/name).
- Date functions: DATE, DATEADD, DATEDIFF, DATENAME, DATEPARSE, DATEPART, DAY, MONTH, YEAR, QUARTER, NOW, TODAY, WEEK, ISOYEAR, ISOWEEK, ISOWEEKDAY, ISOQUARTER, MAKEDATE, MAKEDATETIME.
- String functions: CHAR, CONCAT, CONTAINS, ENDSWITH, FINDSTRING, FINDSTRINGEXACT, LEFT, LEN, LOWER, LTRIM, MID, PROPER, REGEXP_EXTRACT, REGEXP_MATCH, REGEXP_REPLACE, REPLACE, RIGHT, RTRIM, SPLIT, STARTSWITH, TRIM, UPPER.
- Type conversion: ATTR, BOOL, DATE, DATETIME, FLOAT, INT, STR, TIME, TOBOOLEAN, TODATE, TODATETIME, TOFLOAT, TOINTEGER, TOSTRING, TOTIME.
- Number functions: ABS, CEILING, FLOOR, INT, LN, LOG, LOG10, MAX, MIN, MOD, PERCENTILE, RANK, ROUND, SIGN, SQRT, SUM, TRUNC.
- Aggregate functions: AVG, COUNT, COUNTD, MAX, MEDIAN, MIN, PERCENTILE, STDEV, SUM, VAR.
- FIXED LOD examples and include/exclude semantics.
- Use Include/Exclude LODs for controlling granularity and aggregation.
- Custom table calculations — many possibilities.
- Use computed table calculations and specify compute using to make Quick Table Calculation behave correctly.

Data source handling & cleaning
- Split and custom split fields from the datasource.
- Use custom split: split all preserve first and second values, etc.
- Connect to PDF data: scan PDF for tables (Tableau supports PDF connectors in some cases).
- Connect to Microsoft SQL Server → New custom SQL.
- Use manage metadata to change field display names in workbook.
- Change data type and insert corresponding values list “add values from”.
- Change numbers to strings to create relationships where needed.
- To edit connection might take time — be patient.
- To close a data source: go to a worksheet and hit Close.
- To remove tables with warning signs if you want to remove errors.
- To show fields in View Data — use show fields.
- To replace data source and ensure sheets are updated.
- Multiple Excel workbook differences can lead to different Tableau displays — be cautious.
- When you close data source and pop-up appears, it means there are sheets that still use that data source — navigate and replace the datasource.

Data validation & checks
- Data validation in Excel: Sort & Filter → sort on specific columns, then use the counts shown at the bottom to validate entries.
- View data / show underlying to check rows and to split data to verify values.
- Use a fake data generator to create confidential data for outsourcing or sharing.
- Use small dummy Excel to test formatting, show/hide, and container behavior.

Interactivity: show/hide, hide headers, show empty columns
- Show empty columns and show missing values: enable domain members or include missing values.
- Show / hide headers and unhide fields: Analysis → Reveal Hidden Data or use show headers from Row & Columns.
- Show/Hide button in the same container as filters but within another container — separate from filters so blank will automatically resize.
- Put filters in containers to let them resize when you click hide/show.
- When using show/hide: if you don’t see the pin, check container type; nested containers behave differently.
- Use placeholders and ensure distribute contents evenly for hidden sheets to display correctly.
- Hiding special characters (e.g., 0): Format measure pill → Format → Pane → Special Values → Hide.

Formatting: filters, fonts, spacing, icons
- To format filter: Format → Format Filter and set controls in drop-down.
- To change number formatting globally: Default Properties → Number Format.
- For font size jumps: sometimes formatting behavior differs between sheet and dashboard.
- Use left padding for filters so words aren’t too close to the filter edge.
- Use spacing in Labels (Marks → Label → Spacing) to adjust text spacing.
- When text doesn't fit (#####), check outer padding or fixed size constraints.
- If text alignment is off, check Text mark spacing for extra spaces.
- Font size and alignment issues: use the Layout pane and check fixed heights.

Images & shapes
- Create a folder in File Explorer for all images used in the workbook.
- Move all image files into that images folder by dragging.
- To view images without clicking each one, use File Explorer.
- Resize images and keep sizes consistent. Use Paint or Canva to edit images and reduce blank space.
- Set fixed width/height for images to keep consistency or distribute contents evenly in container.
- To load custom shapes: go to My Tableau Repository → Shapes and reload shapes in Tableau.
- Replace images by saving a new file with the same name — Tableau may auto update if referencing the path.
- To paste or replace images in PowerPoint, use Send to Back / Send Backwards properly.

Presentation & assets
- Copy dashboards from sheets to sheets; when pasting content it may become floating.
- To make two images equal size and equal blank spaces, edit externally (Paint / Canva).
- For overlay instructions, create an overlay image and place on top with transparency and navigation to exit.
- Capture screenshot with CopyFish or other screenshot tools.

Performance & troubleshooting
- If the workbook froze: save (check saved time in File Explorer), then close and reopen.
- If formatting disappears: investigate sheet-level formatting vs dashboard-level or container differences.
- If a view doesn’t resize, remove it and place back again.
- If a filter formatting disappears, reformat the filter at the sheet level.
- Recreate view side by side on the computer view if visual copy doesn't match.
- When copying and replacing values into duplicated views, it might take awhile — you can cancel and switch items until they come from same table to speed up.
- When a sheet is hidden but used in another sheet, removing/hiding may not behave as expected — check sheet usage across workbook.
- When Tableau recovers a version, it may be in a temp folder; be careful.
- For large datasets, use extracts to improve responsiveness.
- Use Analyze → Table Layout → Show Filter Label to help users see which filter applies to rows/columns.
- To check what dashboard a sheet belongs to, inspect sheet usage or right click sheet → See Where Used.
- If the workbook uses different Excel tables/workbooks, outputs can vary; standardize input.

Advanced tips & tricks
- Row banding for highlight table may not work — mark-based coloring differs from table banding.
- To split data in datasource: use split or custom split and preserve first/second values as needed.
- To count number of fields within dimensions: convert dimension to measure.
- Use ATTR for single-valued attribute retrieval.
- Dragging a dimension on top of another creates a hierarchy.
- Pages shelf for paginated views.
- Use Tableau zipping hack: change .twb or .twbx to .zip to inspect underlying files (careful).
- Use Preferences.tps to insert custom palettes (must format properly).
- Drag multiple fields into Details to enrich mark-level detail.
- Use Analysis → Table Layout options to show filter labels for rows/columns.
- To select all colors in a color picker: hold Shift, click first color, then scroll and click last color.
- For icons and alt codes: https://www.alt-codes.net/
- For replacing color images online: https://www.imgonline.com.ua/eng/replace-color.php and https://www.fotor.com/photo-editor-app/editor/basic

Small practical tricks
- Duplicate similar views and replace values to preserve formatting; keep previous field and lay another field on top to preserve formatting.
- Duplicate filters to avoid redundancy when needed.
- Use distribute contents evenly to space items in container.
- Use shift while dragging floating objects into containers to force placement.
- Use spacer and reduce font size and change font color to match background when hiding items visually.
- Drag floating objects into containers by holding Shift when dragging.
- Create blank objects with small height as separators or to create dynamic spacing.
- Create a calculated field named One = 1 for highlight tables.
- For overlapping mark visuals, turn stack marks off and adjust mark size.
- For copying color code: right-click on color legend or color pill and copy the hex.
- To create histograms: use Show Me → Histogram and edit quantity bin.
- To make a fixed-size table: choose Fit → Entire View or set fixed height/width.
- To set default aggregation or default number format: Default Properties in the Data pane.
- To see the status bar summary: hover at the bottom to view sum for selected marks.

Miscellaneous nitty-gritty & notes
- "This shit mess with the formatting" — recognize that nested containers, floating vs tiled, and copying between workbooks can break formatting unexpectedly.
- When formatting title colors, make titles different colors to highlight changed fields.
- All functions are Blue but Logical functions are Black in the formula editor.
- Use Clear manual sizing to revert spacing back to defaults.
- Quick Table Calculations: compute using scope properly (table across vs table down).
- Show hidden fields: Analysis → Reveal Hidden Data.
- Show excluded values: re-open the filter and select to include excluded members.
- Copy image vs screen capture: prefer copying the dashboard image or exporting properly.
- Send to back in PowerPoint places the image all the way back; send backwards moves back one.
- When text mark shows unexpected spacing, check for hidden whitespace characters in text marks.
- To count fields within a dimension: convert to measure and use COUNT.
- Sometimes to copy formatting or formatting doesn't persist — consider copying a previous working version of the sheet.
- To fix huge font jumps and sizing issues, inspect sheet vs dashboard formatting; you may need to reapply formatting from sheet-level.
- To replace pictures dynamically: replace the image file with the same name and Tableau will auto-update the referenced image.
- When edits don’t show in dashboard view, try clearing filters and reapplying, or copying an older version of the dashboard.

